Here's how to implement all three:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with back command and unsaved-changes flag

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Back()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/gesture back button in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom `BackButtonBehavior.Command` only intercepts the **shell back button**, not the Android hardware back or swipe-back gesture. To catch those too, override `OnNavigating`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await page.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because the confirmation is async — without it, navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` prevents the navigation when the user taps "Stay".
- The `BackCommand` handles taps on the "Cancel" button; `OnNavigating` handles hardware/gesture back. You may want to set a flag to avoid showing the dialog twice when the command itself calls `GoToAsync("..")`.
